                                        7.18

                                        Assume f∈R on [a.b]. Use Exercise 7.4 to prove that the limit

                                        limn→∞b−an∑k=1nf(a+kb−an)

                                        exist and has the value ∫abf(x)dx. Deduce that

                                        limn→∞∑k=1nnk2+n2=π4,limn→∞∑k=1n(n2+k2)−1/2=log⁡(1+2).

                                        Proof

                                        If f∈R, use Exercise 7.4 we know that for ∀ε>0, there exists δ>0 such that for any partition P with ∥P∥<δ, we have |S(P,f)−∫abf(x)dx|<ε. Let N be an integer such that N>(b−a)/δ, then if n>N, the partition

                                        Pn={a,a+b−an,…,a+n−1n(b−a),b}

                                        has norm ∥Pn∥<δ, choose tk=xx+1 we have

                                        |b−an∑k=1nf(a+kb−an)−∫abf(x)dx|=|S(Pn,f)−∫abf(x)dx|<ε

                                        and the conclusion follows.

                                        Next, we have

                                        limn→∞∑k=1nnk2+n2=limn→∞1n∑k=1n11+k2n2=∫0111+x2dx=arctan⁡x|01=π4,limn→∞∑k=1n(n2+k2)−1/2=limn→∞1n∑k=1n11+k2n2=∫0111+x2dx=log⁡|x+1+x2||01=log⁡(1+2)

                                        7.19

                                        Define

                                        f(x)=(∫0xe−t2dt)2,g(x)=∫01e−x2(t2+1)t2+1dt.

                                        a) Show that g′(x)+f′(x)=0 for all x and deduce that g(x)+f(x)=π/4.

                                        b) Use (a) to prove that

                                        limx→∞∫0xe−t2dt=12π.

                                        Proof

                                        (a) We have

                                        f′(x)=2e−x2(∫0xe−t2dt),∀x∈R

                                        if x=0, we have f(0)=f′(0)=0 and g(0)=arctan⁡1=π/4. Let

                                        h(t,x)=e−x2(t2+1)t2+1

                                        then D2h=−2xe−x2(t2+1) is continuous on [0,1]×[0,a] for any a>0, use Theorem 7.40, the derivative g′(x) exists for each x∈[0,a] and

                                        g′(x)=∫01−2xe−x2(t2+1)dt=−2e−x2∫01e−x2t2d(xt)=−2e−x2∫0xe−y2dy

                                        thus g′(x)+f′(x)=0 for all x, which means g(x)+f(x) is constant for all x, and we have g(0)+f(0)=π/4.

                                        (b) When t∈[0,1], we have

                                        0<h(t,x)<e−x2(t2+1)<e−x2⟹0<g(x)=∫01h(t,x)dt<e−x2

                                        if x→∞, we have e−x2→0, thus limx→∞g(x)=0, which means limx→∞f(x)=π/4, and the conclusion follows.

                                        7.20

                                        Assume g∈R on [a,b] and define f(x)=∫axg(t)dt if x∈[a,b]. Prove that the integral ∫ax|g(t)|dt gives the total variation of f on [a,x].

                                        Proof

                                        Let ε>0, from g∈R on [a,b] we know |g|∈R on [a,b] by Theorem 7.21. So there exists a partition P1={a=x0,x1,…,xn=x} such that L(P1,|g|)>∫ax|g(t)|dt−ε. For this P1, use Mean Value Theorem we have

                                        ∑k=1n|f(xk)−f(xk−1)|=∑k=1n|∫xk−1xkg(t)dt|=∑k=1n|ck(xk−xk−1)|,|ck|≥infx∈[xk−1,xk]|g(x)|

                                        so we have

                                        ∑k=1n|f(xk)−f(xk−1)|=∑k=1n|ck||(xk−xk−1)|≥L(P1,|g|)>∫ax|g(t)|dt−ε

                                        thus Vf(a,x)≥∫ax|g(t)|dt.

                                        On the other hand, there exists a partition P2∈P[a,x] such that U(P2,g)<∫ax|g(t)|dt+ε, and there exists a partition P3={a=y0,y1,…,ym=x} such that

                                        Vf(a,x)−ε<∑k=1m|f(yk)−f(yk−1)|

                                        If we let P=P2∪P3, with the notation P={a=t0,t1,…,tp=x}, then U(P,g)≤U(P2,g) and

                                        ∑k=1m|f(yk)−f(yk−1)|≤∑k=1p|f(tk)−f(tk−1)|=∑k=1p|∫tk−1tkg(t)dt|=∑k=1n|ck(tk−tk−1)|

                                        with |ck|≤supx∈[xk−1,xk]|g(x)|, thus we can have

                                        Vf(a,x)−ε<∑k=1n|ck(tk−tk−1)|≤U(P,|g|)≤U(P2,g)<∫ax|g(t)|dt+ε

                                        thus Vf(a,x)≤∫ax|g(t)|dt.

                                        7.21

                                        Let f=(f1,…,fn) be a vector-valued function with a continuous derivative f′ on [a,b]. Prove that the curve described by f has length

                                        Λf(a,b)=∫ab∥f′(t)∥dt.

                                        Proof

                                        Let ε>0. Each fi is continuous differentiable on [a,b], so fi∈R[a,b] for i=1,…,n, so we have

                                        ∥f′(t)∥=∑i=1n[fi′(t)]2

                                        is continuous on [a,b], thus uniformly continuous, then ∥f′(t)∥∈R[a,b] and we can find δ>0 such that whenever x,y∈[a,b],|x−y|<δ, we have |∥f′(x)∥−∥f′(y)∥|<ε/(b−a). From ∥f′(t)∥∈R[a,b] we can find a partition Pε of [a,b] such that if P1={x0,x1,…,xm} is a partition finer than Pε, then

                                        |∑k=1m∥f′(tk)∥(xk−xk−1)−∫ab∥f′(t)∥dt|<ε,tk∈[xk−1,xk]

                                        By definition of Λf(a,b), there exists a partition P2 such that Λf(a,b)−ε<Λf(P2)≤Λf(a,b). Let P={s0,s1,…,sp} be a partition finer than P1∪P2 with ∥P∥<δ, then Λf(a,b)−ε<Λf(P)≤Λf(a,b) still holds and

                                        Λf(P)=∑k=1p∥f(sk)−f(sk−1)∥=∑k=1p∑i=1n[fi(sk)−fi(sk−1)]2=∑k=1p∑i=1n[fi′(ξk)]2(sk−sk−1)2=∑k=1p(∑i=1n[fi′(ξk)]2)(sk−sk−1)=∑k=1p∥f′(ξk)∥(sk−sk−1),ξk∈[sk−1,sk]

                                        while the last equality comes from the Mean Value Theorem. We also have

                                        |∑k=1p∥f′(tk)∥(sk−sk−1)−∫ab∥f′(t)∥dt|<ε,tk∈[sk−1,sk]

                                        thus

                                        |Λf(a,b)−∫ab∥f′(t)∥dt|≤|Λf(a,b)−Λf(P)|+|Λf(P)−∫ab∥f′(t)∥dt|≤ε+|Λf(P)−∑k=1p∥f′(tk)∥(sk−sk−1)|+|∑k=1p∥f′(tk)∥(sk−sk−1)−∫ab∥f′(t)∥dt|=2ε+|∑k=1p∥f′(ξk)∥(sk−sk−1)−∑k=1p∥f′(tk)∥(sk−sk−1)|=2ε+∑k=1p|∥f′(ξk)∥−∥f′(tk)∥|(sk−sk−1)<2ε+εb−a∑k=1p(sk−sk−1)=3ε

                                        the conclusion follows since ε is arbitrarily chosen.

                                        7.22

                                        If f(n+1) is continuous on [a,x], define

                                        In(x)=1n!∫ax(x−t)nf(n+1)(t)dt.

                                        a) Show that

                                        Ik−1(x)−Ik(x)=f(k)(a)(x−a)kk!,k=1,2,…,n.

                                        b) Use (a) to express the remainder in Taylor's formula (Theorem 5.19) as an integral.

                                        Proof

                                        (a) For k≥1 we have

                                        Ik(x)=1k!∫ax(x−t)kf(k+1)(t)dt=1k!∫ax(x−t)kd[f(k)(t)]=−1k!(x−a)kf(k)(a)−1k!∫axf(k)(t)d(x−t)k=1(k−1)!∫ax(x−t)k−1f(k)(t)dt−f(k)(a)(x−a)kk!

                                        thus the equality holds.

                                        (b) Theorem 5.19 says for x∈[a,b],x≠c there exists x1 between x and c such that

                                        f(x)=f(c)+∑k=1n−1f(k)(c)k!(x−c)k+f(n)(x1)n!(x−c)n

                                        thus the remainder can be expressed as

                                        f(n)(x1)n!(x−c)n=f(x)−f(c)−∑k=1n−1f(k)(c)k!(x−c)k=f(x)−f(c)−∑k=1n−1[Ik−1(x)−Ik(x)]=f(x)−f(c)−I0+In−1=f(x)−f(c)−∫cxf′(t)dt+In−1=In−1=1(n−1)!∫cx(x−t)n−1f(n)(t)dt

                                        7.23

                                        Let f be continuous on [0,a]. If x∈[0,a], define f0(x)=f(x) and let

                                        fn+1(x)=1n!∫0x(x−t)nf(t)dt,n=0,1,2…

                                        a) Show that the nth derivative of fn exists and equals f.

                                        b) Prove the following theorem of M. Fekete: The number of changes in sign of f in [0,a] is not less than the number of changes in sign in the ordered set of numbers

                                        f(a),f1(a),…,fn(a).

                                        c) Use (b) to prove the following theorem of L. Fejér: The number of changes in sign of f in [0,a] is not less than the number of changes in sign in the order set

                                        f(0),∫0af(t)dt,∫0atf(t)dt,⋯,∫0atnf(t)dt.

                                        Proof

                                        (a) The conclusion obviously holds when n=0. And f1(x)=∫0xf(t)dt means (f1)′=f(x). For n≥2 we have

                                        (n−1)!fn(x)=∫0x(x−t)n−1f(t)dt=∑k=0n−1(−1)k(n−1)!k!(n−1−k)!xn−1−k∫0xtkf(t)dt

                                        which means

                                        fn′(x)=(∑k=0n−1[(−1)kxn−1−kk!(n−1−k)!∫0xtkf(t)dt])′=∑k=0n−1[(−1)kxn−1−kk!(n−1−k)!∫0xtkf(t)dt]′=∑k=0n−2(−1)kxn−2−kk!(n−2−k)!∫0xtkf(t)dt+∑k=0n−1(−1)kxn−1−kk!(n−1−k)!xkf(x)=1(n−2)!∫0x(x−t)n−2f(t)dt+∑k=0n−1(−1)kxn−1k!(n−1−k)!f(x)=fn−1(x)+xn−1f(x)(n−1)!∑k=0n−1(n−1)!k!(n−1−k)!(−1)k1n−1−k=fn−1(x)+xn−1f(x)(n−1)!(−1+1)n−1=fn−1(x)

                                        thus (fn)(n)=(fn−1)(n−1)=⋯=(f1)′=f.

                                        (b) Omitted

                                        (c) Omitted

                                        7.24

                                        Let f be a positive continuous function in [a,b]. Let M denote the maximum value of f on [a,b]. Show that

                                        limn→∞(∫abf(x)ndx)1/n=M.

                                        Proof

                                        First we have 0<f(x)≤M on [a,b], thus

                                        0<f(x)n≤Mn⟹∫abf(x)ndx≤∫abMndx=Mn(b−a)⟹(∫abf(x)ndx)1/n≤M(b−a)1/n

                                        Next for ∀ε>0, since f is continuous on [a,b], f attains M at some point in [a,b], thus there exists [c,d]⊂[a,b] with d>c such that

                                        f(x)≥M−ε,x∈[c,d]

                                        choose ε small enough such that M−ε>0, we can have

                                        ∫abf(x)ndx≥∫cdf(x)ndx≥∫cd(M−ε)ndx=(M−ε)n(d−c)⟹(∫abf(x)ndx)1/n≥(M−ε)(d−c)1/n

                                        thus

                                        M−ε=limn→∞(M−ε)(d−c)1/n≤limn→∞(∫abf(x)ndx)1/n≤limn→∞M(b−a)1/n=M

                                        and the conclusion follows.

                                        7.25

                                        A function f of two real variables is defined for each point (x,y) in the unit square 0≤x≤1,0≤y≤1 as follows:

                                        f(x,y)={1,x∈Q2y,x∉Q

                                        a) Compute ∫¯01f(x,y)dx and ∫―01f(x,y)dx in terms of y.

                                        b) Show that ∫01f(x,y)dy exists for each fixed x and compute ∫0tf(x,y)dy in terms of x and t for 0≤x≤1,0≤t≤1.

                                        c) Let F(x)=∫01f(x,y)dy. Show that ∫01F(x)dx exists and find its value.

                                        Proof

                                        (a) Given a partition P={0=x0,x1,…,xn=1}, we have

                                        minx∈[xk−1,xk]f(x,y)={2y,0≤y<1/21,y≥1/2,maxx∈[xk−1,xk]f(x,y)={1,0≤y<1/22y,y≥1/2

                                        thus

                                        ∫¯01f(x,y)dx={1,0≤y<1/22y,y≥1/2,∫―01f(x,y)dx={2y,0≤y<1/21,y≥1/2

                                        (b) If x is fixed, then either x∈Q or not, thus

                                        ∫01f(x,y)dy={∫011dy=1,x∈Q∫012ydy=1,x∉Q

                                        which means ∫01f(x,y)dy=1. For 0≤x≤1,0≤t≤1, we have

                                        ∫0tf(x,y)dy=∫0tdy=t,x∈Q∫0tf(x,y)dy=∫0t2ydy=t2,x∉Q

                                        (c) Since F(x)=∫01f(x,y)dy=1 for x∈[0,1], we have

                                        ∫01F(x)dx=∫011dx=1

                                        7.26

                                        Let f be defined on [0,1] as follows: f(0)=0; if 2−n−1<x≤2−n, then f(x)=2−n for n=0,1,2,…

                                        a) Give two reasons why ∫01f(x)dx exists.

                                        b) Let F(x)=∫0xf(t)dt. Show that for 0<x≤1 we have F(x)=xA(x)−13A(x)2, where A(x)=2−[−log⁡x/log⁡2] and where [y] is the greatest integer in y.

                                        Proof

                                        (a) Reason 1: f is of bounded variation, since f is monotonic increasing and f(x)∈[0,1] for x∈[0,1]. By Theorem 7.28, ∫01f(x)dx exists.

                                        Reason 2: The set of discontinuities of f on [0,1] is the set D={1/2,1/22,…}, which is countable, for ∀ε>0, we can cover each point 1/2k with the interval (1/2k−ε,1/2k+ε), so 1/2k has measure zero, and D has measure zero by Theorem 7.44, and ∫01f(x)dx exists by Theorem 7.48.

                                        (b) For any fixed 0<x≤1, we can find a unique n≥0 such that 2−n−1<x≤2−n, which means

                                        (−n−1)log⁡2<log⁡x≤−nlog⁡2⟹n≤−log⁡xlog⁡2<n+1⟹n=[−log⁡x/log⁡2]

                                        Thus A(x)=2−n. If k>n, then f(t)=2−k for 2−k−1<x≤2−k, thus we have

                                        F(x)=∫0xf(t)dt=∫02−n−1f(t)dt+∫2−n−1xf(t)dt=∑k=n+1+∞∫2−k−12−k2−kdt+∫2−n−1x2−ndt=∑k=n+1+∞2−k(12k−12k+1)+12n(x−2−n−1)=∑k=n+1+∞122k+1+x2n−122n+1=xA(x)+122n+3∑m=0∞14m−122n+1=xA(x)+122n+343−122n+1=xA(x)−122n(12−16)=xA(x)−13A(x)2

                                        7.27

                                        Assume f has a derivative which is continuous and monotonic decreasing and satisfies f′(x)≥m>0 for all x∈[a,b]. Prove that

                                        |∫abcos⁡f(x)dx|≤2m.

                                        Proof

                                        Let g(x)=f′(x)cos⁡f(x), since the function 1/f′(x) is increasing and positive on [a,b], we let B=1/f′(b) and use Theorem 7.37(ii) to have

                                        ∫abcos⁡f(x)dx=∫abg(x)1f′(x)dx=1f′(b)∫x0bg(x)dx=1f′(b)∫x0bdsin⁡f(x)=sin⁡f(b)−sin⁡f(x0)f′(b),x0∈[a,b]

                                        since f′(b)≥m, we have

                                        |∫abcos⁡f(x)dx|≤|sin⁡f(b)−sin⁡f(x0)|m≤2m

                                        7.28

                                        Given a decreasing sequence of real numbers {G(n)} such that G(n)→0 as n→∞. Define a function f on [0,1] in terms of {G(n)} as follows: f(0)=1; if x is irrational then f(x)=0; if x is the rational m/n (in lowest terms), then f(m/n)=G(n). Compute the oscillation ωf(x) at each x in [0,1] and show that f∈R on [0,1].

                                        Solution

                                        If x is irrational in [0,1], for any ε>0 we can find N such that G(n)<ε whenever n>N, for each integer k=1,…,N we can find mk such that

                                        mkk<x<mk+1k,k=1,…,N

                                        define

                                        hk=min(x−mkk,mk+1k−x),k=1,…,N,h0=min(h1,…,hN)>0

                                        then if h<h0, we can conclude that for any y∈(x−h,x+h), either y is irrational, or y is a rational in the form m/n with n>N, thus we have 0≤f(y)≤G(N+1)<ε, which means Ωf(B(x;h)∩[0,1])<ε whenever h<h0, thus wf(x)=0.

                                        If x is rational in [0,1], then we can write x=M/N for some N, thus f(x)=G(N), similar to the procedure above, we can find some h>0 such that for any y∈(x−h,x+h), either y is irrational, or y is a rational in the form m/n with n>N, which means 0≤f(y)≤G(N), so Ωf(B(x;h)∩[0,1])=G(N), and as h→0+, this value remains constant. So ωf(x)=G(N)≥0.

                                        Let D be the set of discontinuities of f on [0,1], then D⊆Q∩[0,1], thus D is countable and has measure zero, by Theorem 7.48 we have f∈R.

                                        7.29

                                        Let f be defined as in Exercise 7.28 with G(n)=1/n. Let g(x)=1 if 0<x≤1, g(0)=0. Show that the composite function h defined by h(x)=g[f(x)] is not Riemann-integrable on [0,1], although both f∈R and g∈R on [0,1].

                                        Proof

                                        We have 0<f(x)≤1 if x∈Q, and f(x)=0 if x∉Q, thus h(x)=1 if x∈Q and h(x)=0 if x∉Q, for any partition P={x0,…,xn} of [0,1], we have

                                        U(P,h)=∑k=1nMk(h)(xk−xk−1)=∑k=1n1(xk−xk−1)=xn−x0=1,L(P,h)=∑k=1nmk(h)(xk−xk−1)=∑k=1n0(xk−xk−1)=0

                                        thus h does not satisfy Riemann's condition on [0,1].

                                        7.30

                                        Use Lebesgue's theorem to prove Theorem 7.49.

                                        Proof

                                        Let D denote the set of discontinuities of f in [a,b] and Dg denote the set of discontinuities of g in [a,b].

                                        (a) If f is of bounded variation on [a,b], then f=f1−f2 where f1,f2 are both monotonic increasing, by Theorem 6.2, D is countable, thus has measure zero.

                                        (b) Let D′ denote the set of discontinuities of f in [c,d]⊆[a,b], then D′⊂D, that f∈R on [a,b] means D has measure zero, so D′ has measure zero, so f∈R on [c,d].

                                        (c) We have D and Dg both have measure zero, if D″ is the discontinuities of f/g on [a,b] if g is bounded away from zero, then D″⊂D∪Dg, which shows D″ has measure zero.

                                        (d) In this case we have D=Dg, thus D has measure zero if and only if Dg has measure zero.

                                        (e) If g is continuous at x∈[a,b], then h is continuous at x, thus the set of discontinuities of h is a subset of Dg, which has measure zero.

                                        7.31

                                        Use Lebesgue's theorem to prove that if f∈R and g∈R on [a,b] and if f(x)≥m>0 for all x∈[a,b], then the function h defined by h(x)=f(x)g(x) is Riemann-integrable on [a,b].

                                        Proof

                                        Let Df denote the set of discontinuities of f in [a,b], and Dg,Dh similarly defined. From h(x)=f(x)g(x) we have log⁡h(x)=g(x)log⁡f(x), thus Dlog⁡h⊆Dg∪Dlog⁡f. Let y(x)=log⁡h(x), then if h is continuous at x, then y is continuous at x, since y=log⁡h means h(x)=ey(x), we see if y is continuous at x, then h is continuous at x, we can conclude Dh=Dlog⁡h, similarly Df=Dlog⁡f. Now f∈R and g∈R means Df and Dg has measure zero, so Dlog⁡f has measure zero, so Dh=Dlog⁡h has measure zero, which means h∈R on [a,b].

                                        7.32

                                        Let I=[0,1] and let A1=I−(13,23) be that subset of I obtained by removing those points which lie in the middle third of I; that is, A1=[0,13]∪[23,1]. Let A2 be that subset of A1 obtained by removing the open middle third of [0,13] and of [23,1]. Continue this process and define A3,A4,… The set C=∩n=1∞An is called the Cantor set. Prove that:

                                        a) C is a compact set having measure zero.

                                        b) x∈C if and only if x=∑n=1∞an3−n, where each an is either 0 or 2.

                                        c) C is uncountable.

                                        d) Let f(x)=1 if x∈C, f(x)=0 if x∉C. Prove that f∈R on [0,1].

                                        Proof

                                        (a) C is bounded since C⊆[0,1], and C=R−A where A=(−∞,0)∪(1,+∞)∪(13,23)∪⋯, notice A is a countable union of open sets, thus is open, so C is closed. Hence C is compact. Let ∀ε>0, since we need ε to be small, we can suppose ε<1/6,let Bi=Ai−Ai+1, thus B1=(13,23), B2=(19,29)∪(79,89), and B3,B4 can be found similarly. Each Bi has length ∥Bi∥=2i−1/3i and has 2i end points. Let Si be obtained from Bi by subtract ε/22i at each end point, which means

                                        S1=(13+ε4,23−ε4),S2=(19+ε16,29−ε16)∪(79+ε16,89−ε16),…

                                        each Si has length 2i−1/3i−ε/2i, and Si∩Sj=∅ for any i≠j, let S=[0,1]−⋃i=1∞Si, then we have C⊆S since Si⊆Bi for all i, the length of S is

                                        ∥S∥=1−∑i=1∞(2i−13i−ε2i)=1−13∑i=0∞(23)i+∑i=1∞ε2i=ε

                                        thus C has measure zero.

                                        since f is a polynomial of degree 2n, we have f(2n+2)(x)=0.

                                        7.34

                                        Given a real-valued function α, continuous on the interval [a,b] and having a finite bounded derivative α′ on (a,b). Let f be defined and bounded on [a,b] and assume that both integrals

                                        ∫abf(x)dα(x),∫abf(x)α′(x)dx

                                        exist. Prove that these integrals are equal. (It is not assumed that α′ is continuous).

                                        Proof

                                        Since both integrals exist, for every ε>0, there exists a partition Pε such that for any partition P finer than Pε and every choice of tk∈[xk−1,xk], we have |S(P,f,α)−∫abf(x)dα(x)|<ε/2, there exists a partition Pε′ such that for any partition P finer than Pε′ and every choice of tk∈[xk−1,xk], we have |S(P,fα′)−∫abf(x)α′(x)dx|<ε/2. Let P=Pε∪Pε′, write P={x0=a,x1,…,xn=b}, consider α(xk)−α(xk−1), use Mean Value Theorem we know there exists ξk∈(xk−1,xk) such that

                                        α(xk)−α(xk−1)=α′(ξk)(xk−xk−1)

                                        since P is finer than Pε′ and ξk∈(xk−1,xk), we have

                                        |∑k=1nf(ξk)α′(ξk)(xk−xk−1)−∫01f(x)α′(x)dx|<ε2

                                        since P is finer than Pε and ξk∈(xk−1,xk), we have

                                        |∑k=1nf(ξk)[α(xk)−α(xk−1)]−∫01f(x)dα(x)|<ε2

                                        thus we have

                                        |∫01f(x)dα(x)−∫01f(x)α′(x)dx|<ε

                                        7.35

                                        Prove the following theorem, which implies that a function with a positive integral must itself be positive on some interval. Assume that f∈R on [a,b] and that 0≤f(x)≤M on [a,b] where M>0. Let I=∫abf(x)dx, let h=12I/(M+b−a) and assume that I>0. Then the set T={x:f(x)≥h} contains a finite number of intervals, the sum of whose length is at least h.

                                        Proof

                                        Let P be a partition of [a,b] such that every Riemann sum S(P,f)=∑k=1nf(tk)Δxk which satisfy S(P,f)>I/2, Split S(P,f) into two parts, S(P,f)=∑k∈A+∑k∈B, where A={k:[xk−1,xk]⊆T} and B={k:k∉A}. So for every k∈B, we can choose some tk such that f(tk)<h. Assume ∑k∈AΔxk≤h, then we have

                                        I2<S(P,f)=∑k∈Af(tk)Δxk+∑k∈Bf(tk)Δxk≤M∑k∈AΔxk+h∑k∈BΔxk≤Mh+h∑k∈BΔxk≤Mh+h(b−a)=h(M+b−a)

                                        divide the positive number M+b−a on both side of the inequality, we get h<h, which is a contradiction.
